So, it's not my specialty, but from the field of ecological psychology as described by Gibson, saying that an owl doesn't understand perceptual phenomena is well, wildly incorrect.

Science ramble!

+block

–block


Basically, for vision, the bodies and perceptual systems of animals (including humans) evolved to gather information about the environment through 1) observing the reflected light in the environment which behaves in specific ways due to physics and 2) intentionally altering their perspective in order to identify elements that change (e.g. whole visual field moves during head movement) and those that do not (e.g. a car or mouse staying still in your visual field as you turn your head). This extends to things like parralax and interpolation associated with perspective. Your perceptual-motor system automatically extracts this information in a predictable manner consistent with the laws of physics (lots of experimental evidence for this), so the idea of  is unnecessary. Owls are way better than us at tracking movement and distance, so it's kind of ridiculous to say that we're better at it than them.

So says Gibson (And his subsequent disciples), anyway. Then you get into things like intrinsic scaling and affordances, which although neat, are literally at least 1.5 grad courses.




ALL THAT RAMBLING ASIDE! I didn't quite understand what was going on in the first read through, possibly due to fatigue. I'll give this another shot when I'm more cognizant. 3 transformer owls, though.

Edit: I also haven't thought about how eco psych applies to this SCP, but I'm not using that as criteria.

